une, an increase of 11.1% from the same period last year. That represented =
a slowdown from the previous quarter, when ad sales rose 13% year-over-year=
. Shares in Alphabet were down 1.4% during after-hours trading after Chief =
Financial Officer Ruth Porat indicated third-quarter operating margins woul=
d be crimped by investments in technical infrastructure and the cost of lau=
nching new hardware products, such as the Pixel phone.

Google=E2=80=99s earnings have been a bit of a roller coast this year: the =
stock dropped around 7 percent after the company reported Q4 2023 earnings =
in late January, and jumped around 10 percent after first quarter results i=
n April; this time the stock is down about 9 percent since the day before e=
arnings, while still being up 21% on the year. These are pretty big swings =
for such an established company, but I suspect they speak to the uncertaint=
y investors have about the long-term impact of AI on Search.

