Notice that the vast majority of the industries on on this list are dominat=
ed by massive companies that compete on scale and distribution. CPG is the =
perfect example: building a =E2=80=9Chouse of brands=E2=80=9D allows a comp=
any like Procter & Gamble to target demographic groups even as they leverag=
e scale to invest in R&D, bring down the cost of products, and most importa=
ntly, dominate the distribution channel (i.e. retail shelf space). Said ret=
ailers, meanwhile, are huge in their own right, not only so they can match =
their massive suppliers at the bargaining table but also so they can scale =
logistics, inventory management, store development, etc. Automobile compani=
es, meanwhile, are not unlike CPG companies: they operate a =E2=80=9Chouse =
of brands=E2=80=9D to serve different demographics while benefitting from s=
cale in production and distribution; the primary difference is that they ma=
ke money through one large purchase instead of over many smaller purchases =
over time.

Similar principles apply to the other companies on this list: all are looki=
ng to reach as many consumers as possible with blunt targeting at best, all=
 benefit from scale, and all are looking to earn significant lifetime value=
 from consumers. And, along those lines, all can afford the expense of TV. =
In fact, the top 200 advertisers in the U.S. love TV so much that they make=
 up 80% of television advertising, despite accounting for only 51% of total=
 advertising (and 41% of digital).

One way to think about what is happening with YouTube specifically and adve=
rtising more broadly is that we are (finally) in the =E2=80=9CInevitable Fa=
ll=E2=80=9D period of TV advertising, at least as far as linear TV advertis=
ing is concerned; YouTube is benefiting, and all of the streaming services =
ad-based plans are potential beneficiaries as well. The great irony here is=
 that this is an unexpected benefit of linear TV=E2=80=99s self-immolation;=
 it was Matthew Ball in a 2023 Stratechery Interview ( https://stratechery.=
com/2023/an-interview-with-matthew-ball-about-disney-streaming-and-the-meta=
