I like to talk about the fact that pay-TV has gone through three waves and =
the last one is not one you can reverse, even though you see Paramount and =
Warner and Disney talking about the importance of linear profits.

I talk about the first phase being roughly 2000 to maybe 2012. This was a p=
eriod of time in which pay-TV was consistently getting better, it was getti=
ng much better. You had more programming, more RSNs, better programming, =
=E2=80=9CMad Men=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9CBreaking Bad=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9CGame of=
 Thrones=E2=80=9D. The problem is it was becoming a little bit too expensiv=
e for the average American. This is your overserving problem, and at the sa=
me time you had Netflix and Hulu coming up.

Phase two runs from 2012 to 2018 and contrary to popular belief, pay-TV kep=
t getting better. You still had more RSNs, you had peak TV happening. The p=
roblem is you were exacerbating that same trend while you were simultaneous=
ly having original content start at the streaming services. But to rebut th=
at, you also had the emergence of vMVPDs. In some regards, TV=E2=80=99s sti=
ll getting better but you=E2=80=99re going to pay less. So, the first is it=
 keeps getting better but it=E2=80=99s getting too expensive. The second is=
 there=E2=80=99s now original content which sits outside of pay-TV, but pay=
-TV is still getting better and now it=E2=80=99s finally getting cheaper=E2=
=80=A6

But then phase three is unique. For the first time in pay-TV=E2=80=99s hist=
ory, it got worse and that=E2=80=99s important. The price kept going up. Vi=
rtual MVPDs started jacking their rates up $10, $15 in a year, but for the =
first time content started getting harvested out. You had Paramount or at t=
he time CBS say actually the sequel to =E2=80=9CThe Good Wife=E2=80=9D, tha=
t=E2=80=99s only going to be on CBS All Access. You had Disney say we=E2=80=
=99re going to greenlight =E2=80=9CThe Mandalorian=E2=80=9D and the Marvel =
series. That=E2=80=99s not going to go into linear, it=E2=80=99s only going=
 to be on streaming. We had Paramount Global say actually =E2=80=9C1923=E2=
=80=9D that was going to debut on linear, now we=E2=80=99re going to put it=
 on streaming. This kept happening. And in fact, just last year you had Dis=
ney take the 36th season of =E2=80=9CDancing with the Stars=E2=80=9D, a sho=
w that had been on ABC, the broadcast network, for nearly 20 years, and the=
y said it=E2=80=99s only going to be on Disney Plus. And so for the first t=
ime, if you take a look over the last eighteen months, pay-TV penetration h=
as imploded, because the product has gotten worse. For Peacock, NBCUniversa=
l basically said, =E2=80=9CEvery high-quality show that we have in developm=
ent for our broadcast network or our cable networks like USA isn=E2=80=99t =
even going to start there.=E2=80=9D FX in 2019 announced that they were goi=
ng to double their original programming hours. Then in 2020, Disney said, =
=E2=80=9CActually FX on Hulu is going to get half of that, it=E2=80=99s nev=
er going to show up on FX=E2=80=9D. And by the way, everything that does ap=
pear on FX is going to be on Hulu twelve hours later with or without ads. T=
here=E2=80=99s kind of no turning that around.

I wrote =E2=80=9CTV Advertising=E2=80=99s Surprising Strength =E2=80=94 And=
 Inevitable Fall=E2=80=9D in 2016, and my thesis was that linear TV and lin=
ear TV advertisers would collapse together, as the former was outcompeted b=
y online entertainment (including streaming), and the latter faced challeng=
es from direct-to-consumer niche-focused competitors that were better able =
to leverage direct response advertising. Ball=E2=80=99s phase three, though=
, meant that TV actually self-destructed more quickly than TV-focused adver=
tisers came under pressure; moreover, the relative strength of the latter w=
as enhanced by things like ATT that increased the cost of direct response a=
dvertising (above-and-beyond the increased ability of Meta and Google to ta=
ke the profits of direct-to-consumer competitors ( https://stratechery.com/=
