The end result is that there are still a lot of brand advertising dollars o=
ut there looking for places other than linear to spend, and the easiest pla=
ces to spend is connected TV.

Network and the Web=E2=80=99s AI Problem
--------------------------------

That leaves the real change in Google=E2=80=99s business: Google Network, w=
hich includes AdMob (for in-app advertising), AdSense (for Google ads on we=
bsites), and Ad Manager (for placing ads from multiple networks, including =
AdSense, across multiple websites). Network has been growing more slowly th=
an Google Sites (including YouTube) revenue for years, but as the chart abo=
ve shows, there was a definite inflection point in 2023: Search and YouTube=
 returned to increasing growth after the COVID and ATT slowdowns, while Net=
work started to outright decline, including a significant drop this quarter=
.

Network doesn=E2=80=99t get much attention in management commentary or anal=
yst questions, probably because it=E2=80=99s been written off as a shrinkin=
g portion of Google=E2=80=99s revenue for years. I think, though, the timin=
gs of the shifts in the chart above give us some clues about what is happen=
ing.

The first factor is ATT. While I have primarily focused on the impact of AT=
T on YouTube, particularly the way in which the connection between ads on Y=
ouTube and conversions on 3rd-party websites and apps was severed, the impa=
ct on Network should have been even greater, given that not just conversion=
s but also ads are placed on 3rd-party properties. I think that this is the=
 most likely explanation for why Network revenue growth rates stopped track=
ing Search and YouTube.

The second factor is where I do think we are starting to see the impact of =
Search Generative Experiences (SGE) i.e. Google=E2=80=99s AI-generated sear=
ch results. Google turned on SGE for everyone halfway through last quarter,=
 which is probably why Network revenue accelerated its decline from -1% yea=
r-over-year in Q1 to -5% year-over-year in Q2; if this thesis is correct th=
an the decline should be even higher this quarter.

Keep in mind that two of the arguments as to why generative AI won=E2=80=99=
t hurt Google Search too badly is that (1) most searches are non-commercial=
 in nature and (2) Google can figure out how to incorporate ads into genera=
tive search results. Notice, though, that neither of these alleviate the pa=
in for 3rd-party websites: those =E2=80=9Cnon-commercial=E2=80=9D searches =
used to drive people to websites with display ads, while ads in generative =
results will compete with whatever links SGE does offer users to go elsewhe=
re. In short, Google Search may be ok in the age of AI, at least for now, b=
ut there is starting to be real evidence that websites will suffer.

